Definition 3.8. The category $\mathbf{EG}$ is defined as follows: (1) Objects are morphisms of $G$-spaces $X\rightarrow G$ (not necessary weak equivalences), such that $X$ is a cofibrant $G$-space and weakly equivalent to $G$. (2) the morphisms $\mathbf{EG}(X\rightarrow G,Y\rightarrow G)$ are given by the commutative diagram of $G$-spaces. $\xymatrix{X\ar[dr]_{-}{}\ar[rr]_{-}{\sim}&&Y\ar[dl]^{-}{}\\ &\mathrm{G}&}$
Definition 3.1 To equip an algebraic theory $\cal L$ with semi-closed structure is to give retractions ${\cal L}(n+1)\,\triangleleft\,{\cal L}(n)$, $\rho:{\cal L}(n)\to{\cal L}(n+1)$ and $\lambda:{\cal L}(n+1)\to{\cal L}(n)$ the retraction and section, natural in $n$ and compatible with the actions ${\cal L}(m)\times{\cal L}(n)^{m}\to{\cal L}(n)$ and ${\cal L}(m+1)\times{\cal L}(n)^{m}\to{\cal L}(n+1)$. A $\lambda$-theory is an algebraic theory $\cal L$ equipped with semi-closed structure. Let $\cal L$ and $\cal M$ be $\lambda$-theories. A map ${\cal L}\to{\cal M}$ of $\lambda$-theories is a map of algebraic theories which commutes with retraction $\rho$ and section $\lambda$.
Definition 4.6 The $\lambda$-theory ${\cal U}_{A}$ of a $\Lambda$-algebra $A$ is the theory of the reflexive universal $U\in P(A)$.
Definition 2.1 An algebraic theory $\cal T$ is first a functor ${\cal T}:{\mathbf{F}}\to{\bf Sets}$: so we have sets ${\cal T}(n)$ of $n$-ary multimaps with variable renamings. In addition, $\cal T$ is equipped with projections ${\bf pr}_{1},\cdots,{\bf pr}_{n}\in{\cal T}(n)$ including as special case the identity ${\bf id}\in{\cal T}(1)$. Finally there are compositions ${\cal T}(n)\times{\cal T}(m)^{n}\to{\cal T}(m)$ which are associative, unital, compatible with projections and natural in $n$ and $m$ (or dinatural in $m$). A map $F:{\cal S}\to{\cal T}$ of algebraic theories is a natural transformation with components $F_{n}:{\cal S}(n)\to{\cal T}(n)$ preserving projections and composition.
Definition 2.8 A presheaf $X$ over an algebraic theory $\cal T$ is a functor $X:{\mathbf{F}}\to{\bf Sets}$ equipped with an action $X(m)\times{\cal T}(n)^{m}\to X(n)$ compatible with the operations of $\cal T$. A map of presheaves is a functor commuting with the action of $\cal T$.
Definition 4.1 A $\Lambda$-algebra is an algebra for the the initial $\lambda$-theory $\Lambda$.
Definition 2.2 An algebra for an algebraic theory $\cal T$ is a set $A$ with an associative unital action ${\cal T}(n)\times A^{n}\to A$ of $\cal T$, natural in $n$. If $A$ and $B$ are ${\cal T}$-algebras then a homomorphism from $A$ to $B$ consists of a map $f:A\to B$ respecting the actions in the sense that the evident diagram commutes.
Definition 2.3. A torsion theory for a category $\mathcal{C}$ is a pair $(\mathscr{T},\mathscr{F})$ of classes of objects $\mathcal{C}$ such that (1) $\operatorname{Hom}(T,F)=0$ for all $T\in\mathscr{T},F\in\mathscr{F}$. (2) If $\operatorname{Hom}(C,F)=0$ for all $F\in\mathscr{F}$, then $C\in\mathscr{T}$. (3) If $\operatorname{Hom}(T,C)=0$ for all $T\in\mathscr{T}$, then $C\in\mathscr{F}$. In that case, $\mathscr{T}$ is called a torsion class and while $\mathscr{F}$ is called a torsion-free class.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a Grothendieck category. A direct system of objects of $\mathcal{C}$, $(M_{\alpha}\mid\alpha\leq\lambda)$, is said to be a continuous system of monomorphisms if $M_{0}=0$, $M_{\beta}=\varinjlim_{\alpha<\beta}M_{\alpha}$ for each limit ordinal $\beta\leq\lambda$ and all the morphisms in the system are monomorphisms. Let $\mathcal{S}$ be a class of objects which is closed under isomorphisms. An object $M$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be $\mathcal{S}$-filtered if there is a continuous system $(M_{\alpha}\mid\alpha\leq\lambda)$ of subobjects of $M$ which is $M=M_{\lambda}$ and $M_{\alpha+1}/M_{\alpha}$ is isomorphic to an object of $\mathcal{S}$ for each $\alpha<\lambda$.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathscr{F}$ be a class of objects of $\mathcal{C}$. A morphism $\phi:F\rightarrow M$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be an $\mathscr{F}$-precover of $M$ if $F\in\mathscr{F}$ and if $\operatorname{Hom}(F^{\prime},F)\rightarrow\operatorname{Hom}(F^{\prime},M)\rightarrow 0$ is exact for every $F^{\prime}\in\mathscr{F}$. If any morphism $f:F\rightarrow F$ such that $\phi\circ f=\phi$ is an isomorphism, then it is called an $\mathscr{F}$-cover of $M$. If the class $\mathscr{F}$ is such that every object has an $\mathscr{F}$-cover, then $\mathscr{F}$ is called a precovering class. The dual notions are those of $\mathscr{F}$-envelope and enveloping class.
Definition 3.6. Let $\tau_{\mathbf{S}}:\mathbf{SCom}\to\mathbf{S}$ be an extension of $\mathbf{SCom}$ as a $2$-sorted Lawvere theory, where implicitly $\mathbf{SCom}=\mathbf{SCom}_{\mathbb{Z}}.$ Without loss of generality, assume the objects are given by pairs $\left(m|n\right)$ with $m$ and $n$ non-negative integers, such that $\tau_{\mathbf{S}}$ is the identity on objects when $\mathbf{SCom}$ is equipped with the usual sorting. Denote by $\mathbf{S}\left(0|0\right)=:\mathbb{K}$ the initial $\mathbf{S}$-algebra. The free $\mathbf{S}$-algebra $\mathbf{S}\left(m|n\right)$ is called the free $\mathbf{S}$-algebra on $m$ even and $n$ odd generators, and is denoted by $\mathbb{K}\{x^{1},\ldots x^{m};\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{n}\}.$
Definition A.26. Algebraic theories naturally form a $2$-category $\mathscr{A\!T}\!\mathit{h}$. A morphism of algebraic theories $\mathbf{T}\to\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$ is a finite product preserving functor. A $2$-morphism is simply a natural transformation of functors. We will mostly be concerned only with truncation $\mathscr{A\!T}\!\mathit{h}$ to a $1$-category in this paper, and denote it by $\mathbf{ATh}.$
Definition 4.40. Suppose that $\mathbf{E}$ is super Fermat. For each $k\geq 0$, $m,n\geq 0$ the $\left(n|m\right)$-dimensional $k^{th}$ jet algebra is defined to be the supercommutative $\mathbb{K}$-algebra $\mathcal{J}_{n|m}^{k}=\mathbb{K}[x^{1},\ldots,x^{n};\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{m}]/m_% {0}^{k+1}$, where $m_{0}=(x^{1},\ldots,x^{n};\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{m}).$ Similarly for $\mathbf{E}$ Fermat, one has jet algebras $\mathcal{J}_{n}^{k}$.
Definition B.24. A quotient $A\mapsto A/R$ by an equivalence relation is called an effective quotient if the canonical map $A\to A/R$ is an effective epimorphism, i.e. $A/R\cong\varinjlim\left(A\times_{A/R}A\rightrightarrows A\right).$
Definition 4.20. The super Fermat theory $\mathbf{E}$ is $\mathbf{Q}$-reduced if for all $\left(n|m\right)$ the evaluation maps $\mathrm{ev}^{\left(n|m\right)}_{\underline{0}}$ and $\mathrm{ev}^{\left(n|m\right)}_{\underline{1}}$ are injective.
Definition B.6. An algebra for an $\SS$-sorted Lawvere theory $\mathbf{T}$ is simply an algebra for its underlying algebraic theory.
Definition 2.36. Let $\mathbb{K}$ be a commutative ring, $\mathcal{A}$ a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra. An extension of $\mathcal{A}$ (over $\mathbb{K}$) is a surjective $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphism $\pi:\mathcal{A}^{\prime}\to\mathcal{A}.$ A split extension of $\mathcal{A}$ (over $\mathbb{K}$) is an extension $\pi:\mathcal{A}^{\prime}\to\mathcal{A}$ together with a section (splitting) $\iota$ of $\pi$ which is also a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphism. Such a split extension is called a split nilpotent extension if additionally, the kernel $\operatorname{Ker}\left(\pi\right)$ is a nilpotent ideal.
Definition A.5. [5, 3] Given an algebraic theory $\mathbf{T}$, a $\mathbf{T}$-algebra (in $\mathbf{Set}$) is defined to be a finite product preserving functor $A:\mathbf{T}\to\mathbf{Set}.$ $\mathbf{T}$-algebras form a category $\mathbf{T}\mathbf{Alg}$, with natural transformations as morphisms; they span a full subcategory of the functor category $\mathbf{Set}^{\mathbf{T}}$. A category $\mathbf{C}$ is said to be algebraic if it is equivalent to $\mathbf{T}\mathbf{Alg}$ for some algebraic theory.
Definition 3.19. Let $\mathbb{K}$ be a supercommutative ring, $\mathcal{A}$ a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra. A split nilpotent extension of $\mathcal{A}$ is a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$ together with a surjective $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphism $\pi:\mathcal{A}^{\prime}\to\mathcal{A}$ such that $N=\operatorname{Ker}\pi$ is a nilpotent ideal, and a section (splitting) $\sigma$ of $\pi$ which is also a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphism. A (super) Weil $\mathbb{K}$-algebra is an extension of $\mathbb{K}$ which is finitely generated as a $\mathbb{K}$-module.
Definition A.12. Let $\varinjlim\left(R\rightrightarrows A\right)$ be a coequalizer in a category $\mathbf{C}$. It is a reflexive coequalizer if for all objects $C,$ the induced map $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,R\right)\to\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{% C}}\left(C,A\right)\times\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,A\right)$ is injective, and hence determines a relation on the set $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,A\right),$ and moreover, this relation is reflexive.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathbb{K}$ be a commutative ring. A supercommutative superalgebra over $\mathbb{K}$ (or supercommutative algebra) is a $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$-graded associative unital $\mathbb{K}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}=\{\mathcal{A}_{\underline{0}},\mathcal{A}_{\underline{1}}\}$ such that $\mathcal{A}_{\underline{0}}$ is commutative and for every $a\in\mathcal{A}_{\underline{1}}$, $a^{2}=0.$ We say that $a$ is of (Grassman) parity $\epsilon$ if $a\in\mathcal{A}_{\epsilon}$; we say it is even (resp. odd) if $\epsilon={\underline{0}}$ (resp. $\epsilon={\underline{1}}$). Supercommutative superalgebras over $\mathbb{K}$ form a category, denoted by $\mathbf{SCom}_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbf{Alg}$, whose morphisms are parity-preserving $\mathbb{K}$-algebra homomorphisms.
Definition 4.26. Given a super Fermat theory $\mathbf{E},$ we define its $\mathbf{Q}$-reduction $\mathbf{E}_{\mathbf{Q}\mathrm{red}}$ to be the image of $\mathrm{ev}_{\mathbf{Q}}.$ Explicitly, the finitely generated $\mathbf{E}_{\mathbf{Q}\mathrm{red}}$-algebra on the sort $\left(n|m\right)$ is given by $\mathbf{E}_{\mathbf{Q}\mathrm{red}}\left(n|m\right)=\operatorname{Im}\left(% \mathrm{ev}^{\left(n|m\right)}_{\mathbf{Q}}\right)=\mathbf{E}\left(n|m\right)/% \operatorname{Ker}\left(\mathrm{ev}^{\left(n|m\right)}_{\mathbf{Q}}\right).$
Definition B.20. Given an equivalence relation $R\rightarrowtail A\times A,$ one may consider the induced pair of maps $R\rightrightarrows A.$ If the coequalizer of this diagram exists, it is called the quotient object $A/R$ of $A$ by the equivalence relation $R.$
Definition 2.6. [13] An extension $\mathbf{E}$ of $\mathbf{Com}$ is called a Fermat theory if for every $f\in\mathbb{K}\{x,z_{1},\ldots,z_{n}\}$ there exists a unique $\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}\in\mathbb{K}\{x,y,z_{1},\ldots,z_{n}\}$, called the difference quotient, such that $f(x,\mathbf{z})-f(y,\mathbf{z})=(x-y)\cdot\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}(x,y,% \mathbf{z})$ where $\mathbf{z}=(z_{1},\ldots,z_{n})$. A Fermat theory over $\mathbb{Q}$ is a Fermat theory whose structure map factors through $\mathbf{Com}_{\mathbb{Q}}$. Let $\mathbf{FTh}$ (resp. $\mathbf{FTh}_{/\mathbb{Q}}$, $\mathbf{FTh}_{\mathbb{K}}$) denote the full subcategory of $\mathbf{Com}/\mathbf{LTh}$ (resp. $\mathbf{Com}_{\mathbb{Q}}/\mathbf{LTh}$, $\mathbf{Com}_{\mathbb{K}}/\mathbf{LTh}$) consisting of the Fermat theories (resp. Fermat theories over $\mathbb{Q}$, Fermat theories with ground ring $\mathbb{K}$).
Definition A.36. When $F$ is faithful, one calls $\mathbf{T}$ as a sub-theory of $\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$; in this case, $F^{*}(\mathcal{A}^{\prime})$ can be thought of as the underlying $\mathbf{T}$-algebra of a $\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}^{\prime}$, while $F_{!}(\mathcal{A})$ is the free $\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$-algebra generated by a $\mathbf{T}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}$, or its $\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$-completion.
Definition 2.29. Given a Fermat theory $\mathbf{E}$, define $\mathbf{E}_{\mathrm{red}}$ by setting $\mathbf{E}_{\mathrm{red}}(n,1)=\operatorname{Im}\mathrm{ev}^{n}=\mathbf{E}(n,1% )/\operatorname{Ker}(\mathrm{ev}^{n}).$
Definition A.1. [5, 3] An (abstract) algebraic theory is a small category $\mathbf{T}$ with finite products.
Definition 4.1. Given an $\mathcal{A}\in\mathbf{E}\mathbf{Alg}$ and $\mathcal{Q}\in\mathbf{Q}$, a $\mathcal{Q}$-point of $\mathcal{A}$ is a homomorphism $p:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{Q}$; a $\mathbf{Q}$-point of $\mathcal{A}$ is a $\mathcal{Q}$-point for some $\mathcal{Q}\in\mathbf{Q}$.
Definition A.29. An algebraic morphism from one algebraic category $\mathbf{C}$ to another $\mathbf{D},$ is an adjunction $\xymatrix@1{\mathbf{C}\ar@<-0.5ex>[r]_{-}{f_{!}}&\mathbf{D}\ar@<-0.5ex>[l]_{-}% {f^{*}}},$ such that the right adjoint $f^{*}$ preserves sifted colimits. With this notion of morphism, algebraic categories naturally form a $2$-category $\mathscr{A}\!\mathit{lg}\mathscr{C}\!\mathit{at}$, whose $2$-morphisms between $\left(f^{*},f_{!}\right)$ and $\left(g^{*},g_{!}\right)$ are given by natural transformations $\alpha:f^{*}\Rightarrow g^{*}.$ We similarly denote its $1$-truncation by the $1$-category $\mathbf{AlgCat}.$
Definition 4.2. An ideal $P$ of a $\mathbf{E}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be a $\mathbf{Q}$-ideal if $P$ is the kernel of some $\mathbf{Q}$-point $p.$ Denote the set of $\mathbf{Q}$-ideals by $\mathbf{Spec}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(\mathcal{A}\right).$ Let $I$ be an arbitrary ideal of $\mathcal{A}$. Define the $\mathbf{Q}$-radical of $I$ to be the ideal $\mathfrak{Rad}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(I\right)=\mathop{\bigcap_{P\supseteq I}}_{P% \in\mathbf{Spec}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(\mathcal{A}\right)}P.$ We call $\mathfrak{Rad}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(0\right)$ the $\mathbf{Q}$-radical of $\mathcal{A},$ and will denote it by $\mathfrak{R}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(\mathcal{A}\right).$
Definition 2.28. A Fermat theory $\mathbf{E}$ is called reduced if all the evaluation maps (2.4) are injective.
Definition 4.51. A near-point determined $\mathbf{E}$-algebra is flat if the endofunctor $\mathcal{A}\mspace{10.0mu }\mbox{\,\put(-4.73,0.0){$\odot$}\put(-3.33,0.0){% \hbox{$\circ$}}}\mspace{10.0mu }\left(\quad\right):\mathbf{E}\mathbf{Alg}_{% \mathbf{npd}}\to\mathbf{E}\mathbf{Alg}_{\mathbf{npd}}$ preserves finite limits (i.e. is left exact.)
Definition 2.39. A Weil $\mathbb{K}$-algebra is a nilpotent extension of $\mathbb{K}$ (over $\mathbb{K}$) which is finitely generated as a $\mathbb{K}$-module. A formal Weil $\mathbb{K}$-algebra is a nilpotent extension of $\mathbb{K}$ (over $\mathbb{K}$).
Definition A.10. A category $\mathbf{D}$ is said to be sifted if for every finite set $X,$ (regarded as a discrete category) and every functor $F:\mathbf{D}\times X\to\mathbf{Set},$ the canonical morphism $\left({\varinjlim}\prod_{x\in X}F\left(d,x\right)\right)\longrightarrow\prod_{% x\in X}{\varinjlim}F\left(d,x\right)$ is an isomorphism. A sifted colimit in $\mathbf{C}$ is a colimit of a diagram $F:\mathbf{D}\to\mathbf{C},$ with $\mathbf{D}$ a sifted category.
Definition 4.24. Let $\mathbf{E}$ be a super Fermat theory, and let $\mathbf{\Lambda}$ denote the subcategory of $\mathbf{E}$ consisting of the Grassman algebras (Definition 3.4.) The super Fermat theory $\mathbf{E}$ is super reduced if it is $\mathbf{\Lambda}$-reduced.
Definition B.19. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a category with finite products. An equivalence relation on an object $A\in\mathbf{C}$ is a subobject $R\rightarrowtail A\times A$ such that for all objects $C$, $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,R\right)\rightarrowtail\operatorname{% Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,A\right)\times\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,% A\right)$ is an equivalence relation on the set $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{C}}\left(C,A\right).$
Definition 3.7. An extension $\mathbf{S}$ of $\mathbf{SCom}$ is called a super Fermat theory if for every $f\in\mathbb{K}\{x,z_{1},\ldots,z_{n};\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{n}\}$ there exists a unique $\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}\in\mathbb{K}\{x,y,z_{1},\ldots,z_{n};\xi^{1},\ldots,% \xi^{n}\}$ such that $f(x,\mathbf{z},\mathbf{\xi})-f(y,\mathbf{z},\mathbf{\xi})=(x-y)\cdot\frac{% \Delta f}{\Delta x}(x,y,\mathbf{z},\mathbf{\xi}),$ and for every $\varphi\in\mathbb{K}\{x^{1},\ldots,x^{m};\eta,\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{n}\}$ there exists a unique $\frac{\Delta\varphi}{\Delta\eta}\in\mathbb{K}\{x^{1},\ldots,x^{m};\xi^{1},% \ldots,\xi^{n}\}$ such that $\varphi\left(\mathbf{x},\eta,\mathbf{\xi}\right)-\varphi\left(\mathbf{x},% \theta,\mathbf{\xi}\right)=\left(\eta-\theta\right)\cdot\frac{\Delta\varphi}{% \Delta\eta}\left(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{\xi}\right).$ Denote by $\mathbf{SFTh}$ the full subcategory of $2$-sorted Lawvere theories under $\mathbf{SCom}$ consisting of those which are super Fermat theories.
Definition A.17. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a small category. We define $\mathbf{Sind}\left(\mathbf{C}\right)$ to be the free cocompletion of $\mathbf{C}$ with respect to sifted colimits. It is a category under $\mathbf{C},$ $Y_{\mathbf{Sind}}:\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{Sind}\left(\mathbf{C}\right)$ determined uniquely up to equivalence by the property that the functor $Y_{\mathbf{Sind}}$ satisfies the following universal property: For all categories $\mathbf{B}$ with sifted colimits, composition with $Y_{\mathbf{Sind}}$ induces an equivalence of categories $\mathbf{Fun}_{\mathit{sift}}\left(\mathbf{Sind}\left(\mathbf{C}\right),\mathbf% {B}\right)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{-\!\!\!-\!\!\!-\!\!\!-\!\!\!-\!\!\!-% \!\!\!\longrightarrow}}\mathbf{Fun}\left(\mathbf{C},\mathbf{B}\right),$ where $\mathbf{Fun}_{\mathit{sift}}\left(\mathbf{Sind}\left(\mathbf{C}\right),\mathbf% {B}\right)$ is the full subcategory of the functor category $\mathbf{Fun}\left(\mathbf{Sind}\left(\mathbf{C}\right),\mathbf{B}\right)$ spanned by those functors which preserve sifted colimits.
Definition 3.4. Given a $\mathbb{K}$-algebra $\mathcal{R}$, the Grassmann (or exterior) $\mathcal{R}$-algebra on $n$ generators is the free supercommutative $\mathcal{R}$-superalgebra on $n$ odd generators. In other words, it is generated as an $\mathcal{R}$-algebra by odd elements $\xi^{1},\ldots,\xi^{n}$ subject to relations $\xi^{i}\xi^{j}+\xi^{j}\xi^{i}=0.$ Denote this algebra by $\Lambda^{n}_{\mathcal{R}}$ (or simply $\Lambda^{n}$ if $\mathcal{R}=\mathbb{K}$).
Definition 4.29. Let $\mathbf{N}$ denote the class of formal Weil $\mathbb{K}$-algebras. An $\mathbf{E}$-algebra which is $\mathbf{N}$-point determined is said to be near-point determined. Denote the associated subcategory by $\mathbf{E}\mathbf{Alg}_{\mathbf{npd}}.$
Definition B.23. Let $\mathbf{T}$ be an $\SS$-sorted Lawvere theory. An equivalence relation in $\mathbf{T}\mathbf{Alg}$ is called a congruence.
Definition 4.7. If an $\mathbf{E}$-algebra $\mathcal{A}$ satisfies either of the equivalent conditions of Proposition 4.6, it is said to be $\mathbf{Q}$-point determined. Denote the full subcategory of $\mathbf{Q}$-point determined algebras by $\mathbf{E}\mathbf{Alg}_{\mathbf{Q}\mathrm{det}}$. An ideal $I$ is said to be $\mathbf{Q}$-point determined (or $\mathbf{Q}$-radical) if $\mathfrak{Rad}_{\mathbf{Q}}\left(I\right)=I.$
Definition B.1. An $\SS$-sorted Lawvere theory is an algebraic theory $\mathbf{T}$ together with a injection $\varphi_{\mathbf{T}}:\SS\hookrightarrow\mathbf{T}_{0}$ whose image generates $\mathbf{T}$ in the sense of definition A.3. A morphism of $\SS$-sorted Lawvere theories $\left(\mathbf{T},\varphi_{\mathbf{T}}\right)\to\left(\mathbf{T}^{\prime},% \varphi_{\mathbf{T}^{\prime}}\right)$ is a (natural equivalence class of a) morphism of algebraic theories $F:\mathbf{T}\to\mathbf{T}^{\prime}$ such that for all $s\in\SS,$ $F\left(\varphi_{\mathbf{T}}\left(s\right)\right)=\varphi_{\mathbf{T}}^{\prime}% \left(s\right).$ We denote the associated category $\SS\mathbf{LTh}.$ When $\SS$ is a singleton set, we call an $\SS$-sorted Lawvere theory simply a Lawvere theory, and denote the corresponding category by $\mathbf{LTh}.$
Definition 2.33. Let $f:\mathbb{K}^{n}\to\mathbb{K}$ be a function. Given a $k=1,\ldots,n$, we say that $f$ is differentiable in the $k$th variable if there is a unique function $\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x^{k}}:\mathbb{K}^{n+1}\to\mathbb{K}$ such that $f(\ldots,x,\ldots)-f(\ldots,y,\ldots)=(x-y)\cdot\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x^{k}}(% \ldots,x,y,\ldots).$ This $g_{k}$ is then called the difference quotient of $f$ with respect to the $k$th variable. Say that $f$ is differentiable if it is differentiable in all the variables. Given $N>1$, say that $f$ is $N$ times differentiable if $f$ is differentiable and all its difference quotients are $N-1$ times differentiable. Finally, say that $f$ is smooth if it is $N$ times differentiable for all $N$.
Definition A.3. A set $\SS\subset\mathrm{Ob}(\mathbf{T})$ of objects of $\mathbf{T}$ is said to generate $\mathbf{T}$ as an algebraic theory if very object of $\mathbf{T}$ is isomorphic to the product of finitely many objects from $\SS.$
Definition 4.2. We say that field systems $(\EuFrak{F}_{1},\pi_{1},U_{1},\EuFrak{G}_{1})$, $(\EuFrak{F}_{2},\pi_{2},U_{2},\EuFrak{G}_{2})$ are equivalent whenever there is a unitary family $\nu=\{\nu_{a}:H_{1,a}\to H_{2,a}\}$ such that $\nu_{a^{\prime}}U_{1,a^{\prime}a}=U_{2,a^{\prime}a}\nu_{a}\ \ ,\ \ {\mathrm{ad% }}\nu_{a^{\prime}}\circ\jmath_{1,a^{\prime}a}=\jmath_{2,a^{\prime}a}\circ{% \mathrm{ad}}\nu_{a}\ \ ,\ \ \nu_{a}g\nu_{a}^{*}\in G_{2,a}\ \ ,\ \ \nu_{a}% \gamma_{1,a}=\gamma_{2,a}\nu_{a}\ ,$ for all $a\subseteq a^{\prime}$, $g\in G_{a}$.
Definition 2.1. A Morita equivalence is a $\mathbb{K}$-linear functor $F\colon A\to B$ with the property that extension of scalars $\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}A\to\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}B$ along $F$ (i.e. the left Kan extension of $h_{B}\circ F\colon A\to B\to\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}B$ along $h_{A}\colon A\to\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}A$, where $h_{A},h_{B}$ are the Yoneda embeddings) is an equivalence of categories.
Definition 4.9. If $V$ is an $\mathbb{L}$-vector space, denote by ${}^{\sigma}V$ the $\mathbb{L}$-vector space that coincides with $V$ as a group and whose $\mathbb{L}$-action is given by $x\cdot v:=\sigma^{-1}(x)v$ for $x\in\mathbb{L}$ and $v\in V$. Then $\smash{\bigotimes_{\sigma\in G}{}^{\sigma}V}$, where the tensor product is taken over $\mathbb{L}$, can be endowed with the skew-linear $G$-action $\tau(\otimes_{\sigma\in G}v_{\sigma}):=\otimes_{\sigma\in G}v_{\tau^{-1}\sigma}$, for $\tau\in G$. By taking $G$-invariants, we obtain in this way a well-defined functor $\displaystyle\mathrm{Cor}_{\mathbb{L}/\mathbb{K}}\colon\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}% \mathbb{L}\longrightarrow\mathop{\mathsf{Mod}}\mathbb{K}$ $\displaystyle V\mapsto\left(\textstyle\bigotimes_{\sigma\in G}{}^{\sigma}V% \right)^{G}\,.$
Definition 3.5. We will call the model structure of Theorem 3.4 the canonical model structure on $\mathsf{Cat}_{\mathbb{K}}$ and we will denote it by $\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{can}}$.
Definition 4.6. An $\mathbb{L}/\mathbb{K}$-Galois module is an $\mathbb{L}$-vector space $W$ endowed with a left $G$-action which is skew-linear, in the sense that $\sigma(x)\sigma(w)=\sigma(xw)$ for every $x\in\mathbb{L},w\in W$ and $\sigma\in G$. Denote by $\mathop{\mathsf{GalMod}}\mathbb{L}/\mathbb{K}$ the category of $\mathbb{L}/\mathbb{K}$-Galois modules and $G$-equivariant $\mathbb{K}$-linear maps.
